Geospatial Data

There are several common ways to store spatial data:

  • Shapefiles
  • Tabular data with spatial coordinates
  • File geodatabases
  • Raster data
  • KML
  • GeoJSON

Datasets can define a wide variety of features, including:

  • Rasters
  • Points
  • Lines
  • Polygons

For more complicated line and polygon features, a large number of edges and vertices need to be stored in memory alongside feature-level variables. For example, to define a rectangular state like Colorado, we need to specify four different vertices, but well only have one value for the total population of colorado.

Shapefiles and File Geodatabases provide efficient ways to store spatial data. Today well focus on working with points and polygons.

Packages for Geospatial Data in R

There are many overlapping packages for reading, writing, manipulating, and analyzing spatial data. Today well work with some of the more commmon packages.

#install.packages(c("rgdal","sp","maptools","rgeos","ggmap"), dependencies=TRUE)
#Go to Session>Restart R after installing
library(rgdal)
library(sp)
library(ggmap)
library(maptools)

rgdal (Geospatial Data Abstraction Library)

rgdal provides many of the basic functions for working with spatial data in R via external tools (GDAL and PROJ.4). Well read shapefiles and file geodatabases into R with rgdals readOGR function.

sp and maptools

sp and maptools provide more classes, methods, and functions in R for working with spatial data.

ggmap

Built on top of ggplot2, ggmap provides access to a variety of online basemaps.

Reading Shapefiles

A shapefile consists of (as a minimum) three files with the same name but different extensions:

  • .shp shape format
  • .shx shape index format
  • .dbf attributes (i.e.the data!)

There can be a number of other files included with a shapefile. All of these files should be kept together.

nc_counties <- readOGR(dsn="shapefile",layer="NC_Counties")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "shapefile", layer: "NC_Counties"
## with 100 features
## It has 48 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  POP2001 NO_FARMS97 AVG_SIZE97 CROP_ACR97

Note that we set dsn to the folder containing the files making up the shapefile. This address should not have a \ at the end.

class(nc_counties)
## [1] "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"

nc_counties is a SpatialPolygonsDataFrame. This indicates that the object contains both spatial polygons and underlying data. Lets take a look with summary. Its also possible to create SpatialPolygons, SpatialPoints, SpatialPolygonsDataFrame, and SpatialPointsDataFrame objects from scratch in R.

summary(nc_counties[,1:8])

Note the Is Projected: TRUE line towards the top of the summary. This indicates that the data is stored in a projected coordinate system. Projected coordinates project spherical coordinates into a two-dimensional space. They are often accurate for a specific area, but cause distortions on a larger scale (think about the various ways the entire world is often represented on a map).

Geographic coordinates are spherical; the most common example is latitude and longitude. Youll often find data provided in different coordinate systems.

We can get another view of the coordinate system that contains more familiar information with:

showWKT(proj4string(nc_counties))
## [1] "PROJCS[\"Lambert_Conformal_Conic\",GEOGCS[\"GCS_North_American_1983\",DATUM[\"D_North_American_1983\",SPHEROID[\"GRS_1980\",6378137,298.257222101]],PRIMEM[\"Greenwich\",0],UNIT[\"Degree\",0.017453292519943295]],PROJECTION[\"Lambert_Conformal_Conic\"],PARAMETER[\"standard_parallel_1\",34.33333333333334],PARAMETER[\"standard_parallel_2\",36.16666666666666],PARAMETER[\"latitude_of_origin\",33.75],PARAMETER[\"central_meridian\",-79],PARAMETER[\"false_easting\",609601.22],PARAMETER[\"false_northing\",0],UNIT[\"Meter\",1]]"

The PROJC2, Lambert Conformal Conic, describes the projection used, and GEOGCS, gives the underlying geographic coordinate system, GCS North American 1983 is also known as NAD83.

Read more about projected and geographic coordinate systems here.

plot(nc_counties)

(Creating Shapefiles)

We can also create shapefiles and other spatial data types with rgdal. First, we need to point out which fields contain the coordinates, and define the coordinate system.

amst_shp <- amst
coordinates(amst_shp) <- ~longitude+latitude
proj4string(amst_shp) <- CRS("+init=epsg:4326")
#writeOGR(amst_shp,dsn="shapefile","Amst_AirBnB",driver="ESRI Shapefile")

Note: Shapefiles require variable names less than 10 characters. If your variables have longer names, writeOGR will truncate them.

Reading File Geodatabases

File geodatabases are stored in folders ending with .gdb. Your computer treats a geodatabase as a folder with many cryptic looking files inside. (Try opening nc_data.gdb with Windows Explorer or Finder.) Its important not to change or move any of these component files. Well use R to determine whats actually contained in our geodatabase.

fgdb <- "nc_data.gdb"

# List all feature classes in a file geodatabase
print(ogrListLayers(fgdb))
## [1] "nc_cities" "nc_gas"   
## attr(,"driver")
## [1] "OpenFileGDB"
## attr(,"nlayers")
## [1] 2

The available layers in this geodatabase are nc_cities and nc_gas (listed in the first row).

nc_cities <- readOGR(dsn=fgdb,layer="nc_cities")
## OGR data source with driver: OpenFileGDB 
## Source: "nc_data.gdb", layer: "nc_cities"
## with 65 features
## It has 45 fields
class(nc_cities)
## [1] "SpatialPointsDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"

nc_cities is a SpatialPointsDataFrame. Similarly to the nc_counties layer above, this indicates that the layer countains spatial points along with underlying data.

#summary(nc_cities)
plot(nc_cities)

We can quickly plot two layers together using the add parameter (provided they have compatible coordinate systems).

nc_gas <- readOGR(dsn=fgdb,layer="nc_gas")
## OGR data source with driver: OpenFileGDB 
## Source: "nc_data.gdb", layer: "nc_gas"
## with 6510 features
## It has 19 fields
plot(nc_counties)
plot(nc_cities,pch=17,cex=1.5,col="red",add=TRUE)
plot(nc_gas,pch=1,add=TRUE,cex=0.4)

Adding basemaps with ggmap

Changing coordinate systems

Before adding a basemap, we need to convert it to a geographic coordinate system. Well use WGS84, which is encoded by +init=epsg:4326. The ESPG number is just one way to specify a particular coordinate system.

nc_counties_wgs <- spTransform(nc_counties, CRS("+init=epsg:4326"))

With the geographic (i.e.latitude and longitude) coordinates set, we can use the layer to determine a suitable extent for a basemap with bbox, then download the map with getmap.

b <- bbox(nc_counties_wgs)
base <- ggmap(get_map(location = b,source="stamen",maptype="toner-lite"))
base

Reformatting our polygons

However, to actually plot our polygon data, we need to convert the data into a data.frame format with the fortify function to work with ggplot. We need to specify the region option to control what field is used as a feature id in the output.

nc_counties_wgs.f <- fortify(nc_counties_wgs,region="CNTY_FIPS")


class(nc_counties_wgs)
## [1] "SpatialPolygonsDataFrame"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "sp"
class(nc_counties_wgs.f)
## [1] "data.frame"

## 6 -79.25690 36.24196     6 FALSE     1 001 001.1

fortify produces a standard output, and only includes the spatial information, not the underlying data. We need to merge that back into the data.frame with merge. Since we set region="CNTY_FIPS" above, we know we can merge on CNTY_FIPS/id.

nc_counties_wgs.f <- merge(nc_counties_wgs.f,nc_counties,by.x="id",by.y="CNTY_FIPS")
names(nc_counties_wgs.f)

Now we can use ggplot syntax with geom_polygon to plot our polygons.

p1 <- base+
  geom_polygon(data=nc_counties_wgs.f,
               aes(x=long,y=lat,group=group,fill=POP00_SQMI),alpha=0.6,color="black",size=0.5)+
  scale_fill_gradient(low="white",high="blue")+
  theme_nothing(legend = TRUE)

p1

Adding Spatial Points

Spatial points do not need to be fortified since they only need one line per observation. Instead, we only need to make sure they use the same coordinate system, then convert them to a dataframe with as.data.frame. The SpatialPointsDataFrame object will place their longitude in coords.x1 and their latitude in coords.x2.

nc_cities_wgs <- spTransform(nc_cities, CRS("+init=epsg:4326"))
nc_cities_wgs.df <- as.data.frame(nc_cities_wgs)

p1+geom_point(data=nc_cities_wgs.df,aes(x=coords.x1,y=coords.x2,size=(POP2000/1000)),colour="red")
